children.subject:
I took EECS 127 with just 16a and CS 70 and did fine. CS 70 itself isn't really useful in terms of the topics. The most we covered in that class that is even tangentially related to CS 70 is maximum likelihood estimators and covariance matrices, none of which are really covered in that much depth in CS 70 if at all. I've heard that what people found more useful from CS 70 is the "mathematical maturity", and as much as I hate that term being used for gatekeeping from upper divs, I somewhat agree. If you haven't taken 70, then maybe it'd be beneficial to take EECS 16B since that provides this so called "mathematical maturity" while also teaching you concepts that will be useful for 127.

I don't know why you are facing that enrollment issue. Maybe someone else can answer.

history.content:
I'm considering taking eecs 127 in the fall (EECS second-year), and had some questions:

  • having only taken 16a/54 (took both for a potential double major), is it feasible to take 127 at the same time as cs70? or would it be better to wait and take it after completing 70? planning on taking CS170 + EECS126 in the spring
  • was thinking about taking this class as alternative to another class that I have even slimmer chances of getting into; however, for some reason, when I try to set up a swap to put myself on the waitlist, CalCentral says the lecture is closed -- if the class is full, but there are still seats open on the WL, why might this be the case?
